# Q6 DEEP-DIVE : MLIR-core vs CUSTOM-IR vs LLVM-only
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# § I> biggest architectural fork • determines entire compiler
# § I> inputs : ~8 web-searches + S1 Mojo + S6 MLIR/IREE + S10 syntax

§ THE-CHOICE  ← §§ Q6.1 three-options
  A : LLVM-only (Cranelift optional for dev-build)
  B : MLIR-core + custom cssl.* dialects + LLVM-backend
  C : custom CSSLv3-IR + LLVM-backend + SPIRV-translator

§ ASSESSMENT-DIMENSIONS  ← §§ Q6.2
  D1 : time-to-first-pixel @ LoA
  D2 : dual-codegen CPU+GPU cost
  D3 : AD-integration cost (F1 Enzyme)
  D4 : refinement-type integration cost (F2)
  D5 : effect-system integration cost (F3)
  D6 : staging integration cost (F4)
  D7 : debuggability + error-quality
  D8 : compile-speed (dev-loop)
  D9 : ecosystem-leverage (passes + tools)
  D10 : bus-factor / maintainability (solo-dev)
  D11 : future-HW portability
  D12 : learning-curve (Apocky-runway)

§ OPTION-A : LLVM-only  ← §§ Q6.3
  arch : CSSLv3-AST → CSSLv3-HIR(custom) → LLVM-IR → obj
  GPU-path : LLVM-IR → LLVM-SPIRV-translator → SPIR-V
  D1 : ✓ fastest-to-first-pixel (smallest-moving-parts)
  D2 : ◐ works but SPIR-V-translator known-limited
       ○ ¬ supports all-SPIR-V-ops cleanly
       ○ GPU-specific-concepts (workgroup shared-mem) → awkward LLVM-IR
  D3 : ✓ Enzyme = native-LLVM-pass ≡ drop-in
  D4 : ◐ refinement = pure-frontend-check • no IR-support needed
  D5 : ◐ effect-discharge = pure-frontend-check
  D6 : ✗ staging hard • LLVM-IR too-low-level for scene-eval-specialization
       ○ W! lift-back-up to AST ≡ awkward
  D7 : ✗ debug : LLVM-IR strips-high-level-semantics
  D8 : ✓ compile-speed OK (LLVM-only stack)
  D9 : ◐ only-LLVM-passes available • miss Linalg affine
  D10 : ✓ smallest-surface-area • fewest-deps • solo-dev-tractable
  D11 : ◐ CPU+GPU only-via-LLVM • no TPU/NPU path
  D12 : ✓ LLVM well-documented • Apocky has prior-Rust-LLVM-exposure
  SCORE : best for time-to-pixel • worst for F4-staging + future-HW

§ OPTION-B : MLIR-core + custom-dialects  ← §§ Q6.4
  arch : CSSLv3-AST → cssl.* dialects → standard-dialects
         → {LLVM-dialect → obj • SPIRV-dialect → SPIR-V-blob}
  D1 : ✗ slow-first-pixel (large upfront infrastructure)
  D2 : ✓ best-in-class : dual-lowering native to MLIR
       ○ IREE proves-pattern production-grade
  D3 : ◐ Enzyme-MLIR exists • less-mature than LLVM-Enzyme
       ○ workaround : lower to LLVM-dialect → LLVM-Enzyme → back
  D4 : ✓ refinement-types can-be IR-attributes on cssl.sdf ops
       ○ propagation via pattern-rewrites (TableGen)
  D5 : ✓ effect-system = cssl.effect dialect
       ○ handlers lower via cssl.handle → scf + func dialects
  D6 : ✓✓ staging native-fit : Transform-dialect programmable-schedules
       ○ CGO'25 paper : Transform-dialect-expose-compiler-internals
       ○ CSSLv3 @staged → Transform-schedule ≡ first-class
  D7 : ✗✗ debug-hard : "multi-dialect lowering hard to step through"
       ○ Ramalho-2024 : "steep learning curve hinders adoption"
       ○ Mojo-team themselves cite productivity-challenge
  D8 : ◐ MLIR-pass-overhead + dialect-conversion = slower-compile
  D9 : ✓✓ reuse : arith scf cf func memref gpu llvm spirv linalg affine
       ○ IREE patterns + Transform-dialect + upstream-optimizations
  D10 : ✗✗ bus-factor risk : MLIR complex • solo-dev-challenging
        ○ C++ templates + TableGen + sparse-docs
        ○ Lei.Chat 2022 "5y to mature ecosystem" ≡ 2027-mature
  D11 : ✓✓ TPU/NPU/FPGA all-addressable via dialect-bridging
  D12 : ✗✗ steepest-curve • "sparse documentation" + C++ templates
  SCORE : best for F4 + future-HW + ecosystem • worst for bus-factor + debug + learning

§ OPTION-C : custom CSSLv3-IR + LLVM-backend  ← §§ Q6.5
  arch : CSSLv3-AST → CSSLv3-HIR → CSSLv3-MIR → LLVM-IR → obj
         GPU : CSSLv3-MIR → custom-SPIRV-emitter → SPIR-V
  D1 : ◐ medium-first-pixel (IR + transforms + SPIRV-emitter all-custom)
  D2 : ✓ total-control over CPU+GPU lowering
       ○ cost : hand-written SPIRV-emitter = many-months
  D3 : ✓ Enzyme @ LLVM-bottom ≡ clean drop-in
  D4 : ✓ refinement-types first-class-in-IR
  D5 : ✓ effect-system first-class-in-IR
  D6 : ✓ staging native : IR can-have stage-markers
  D7 : ✓✓ excellent : ∀ IR-node carries-CSSLv3-semantics
        ○ error-messages map-directly to source
  D8 : ✓ compile-speed : control-own-pipeline
  D9 : ✗✗ rebuild-everything : no reuse-of-MLIR-passes
        ○ polyhedral analysis • tiling • fusion all-from-scratch
  D10 : ◐ bus-factor medium • docs-by-Apocky only
         ○ but : simpler-than-MLIR overall (smaller-scope)
  D11 : ✗ future-HW : rebuild-lowering per-target
  D12 : ◐ medium-curve : need-to-design-IR + build-infrastructure
  SCORE : best for D7 + F1..F4 cleanliness • worst for D9 ecosystem

§ COMPARATIVE-TABLE  ← §§ Q6.6
             A:LLVM   B:MLIR   C:custom-IR
  D1 pixel    ✓✓       ✗        ◐
  D2 dual     ◐        ✓✓       ✓
  D3 F1-AD    ✓✓       ◐        ✓✓
  D4 F2-ref   ◐        ✓        ✓
  D5 F3-eff   ◐        ✓        ✓
  D6 F4-stg   ✗        ✓✓       ✓
  D7 debug    ✗        ✗✗       ✓✓
  D8 speed    ✓        ◐        ✓
  D9 reuse    ◐        ✓✓       ✗✗
  D10 bus     ✓        ✗✗       ◐
  D11 HW      ◐        ✓✓       ✗
  D12 learn   ✓        ✗✗       ◐

§ TIE-BREAKING CRITERIA  ← §§ Q6.7
  I> Apocky = solo-dev • D10 bus-factor weight = 3×
  I> LoA-ship-first • D1 time-to-pixel weight = 2×
  I> bug-thesis-requires F4-staging working • D6 weight = 2×
  I> future-HW ¬ 2026-priority • D11 weight = 0.5×
  I> learn-curve W! be tractable-solo • D12 weight = 2×
  
  weighted-scores :
    A : 3×✓✓ + 2×✓✓ + 2×✗ + 0.5×◐ + 2×✓ = solid for near-term
    B : 3×✗✗ + 2×✗ + 2×✓✓ + 0.5×✓✓ + 2×✗✗ = blocked on bus-factor
    C : 3×◐ + 2×◐ + 2×✓ + 0.5×✗ + 2×◐ = tractable + semantically-clean

§ DECISION : HYBRID A→C EVOLUTION  ← §§ Q6.8 ★
  
  STAGE-0..3 (year-1) : OPTION-A (LLVM-only custom-HIR)
    ○ CSSLv3-AST → CSSLv3-HIR → LLVM-IR → obj
    ○ GPU via LLVM-SPIRV-translator (known-limited • acceptable)
    ○ Enzyme = native LLVM-pass plugin
    ○ get LoA-to-first-pixel fastest • prove F1..F3 work
    ○ F4-staging minimal @ this-stage (AST-level-only)
  
  STAGE-4..6 (year-2) : TRANSITION-TO-CUSTOM-MIR
    ○ insert CSSLv3-MIR between HIR and LLVM-IR
    ○ MIR carries effect-rows + refinement-types first-class
    ○ improves D7 debug quality
    ○ enables real-F4-staging via MIR-level-transforms
    ○ write custom-SPIRV-emitter from-MIR (replace LLVM-SPIRV-translator)
  
  STAGE-7+ (year-3+) : OPTIONAL MLIR-BRIDGE
    ○ if community forms + ecosystem-leverage worthwhile
    ○ wrap CSSLv3-MIR as MLIR-dialect (cssl)
    ○ interop with IREE/Transform-dialect opportunistically
    ○ ¬ commit before evidence demands it

§ RATIONALE  ← §§ Q6.9
  ✓ Option-A minimizes-risk year-1 : Rust→LLVM well-trodden
  ✓ Enzyme-LLVM-pass drops-in without MLIR-complexity
  ✓ Apocky-solo-dev-friendly : smaller-surface-area
  ✓ Custom-MIR year-2 when F1..F3 proven + semantics-stable
    ¬ pre-mature-IR-design before-knowing-what-LoA-actually-needs
  ✓ MLIR-bridge year-3 reversible : cssl-dialect can-wrap custom-MIR
  ✗ ¬ pure-MLIR now : bus-factor + learn-curve = project-death-risk-solo
  ✗ ¬ pure-custom-all-at-once : throwing-away Enzyme + LLVM-SPIRV = waste

§ IMPLICATIONS for SPECS  ← §§ Q6.10
  specs/02_IR.csl W! describe :
    year-1 : CSSLv3-HIR (SSA + effect-row + refinement-attr)
             → LLVM-IR via standard-lowering
             → GPU via LLVM-SPIRV-translator (commit-accepting-limits)
    year-2 : add CSSLv3-MIR layer (HIR ↛ MIR ↛ LLVM)
    year-3 : optional MLIR-bridge

